  &lt;div style=&quot;margin: 5px 0px 5px 0px; font-family: monospace;&quot;&gt;
   &lt;br/&gt;
   Mike Kelly &#60;mikekelly321@...&#62; hat am 3. Januar 2012 um 16:52 geschrieben:
   &lt;br/&gt;
   &lt;br/&gt;
   &#62;
   &lt;br/&gt;
   &#62; - What the resource does upon POST is determined by understanding the
   &lt;br/&gt;
   &#62; semantics of the application it is part of
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;No, this is where you get it wrong. The resource has no idea what the application is. Especially is it not bound to whatever the client expects.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;Hypermedia received by the client tells clients something about the nature of certain resources (e.g. an HTML &#60;img&#62; element, an AtomPub &#60;collection&#62; element, an OpenSearch &#60;Query&#62; element or a hypothetical order-processor semantic defined in some procurement media type).&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;An yes, the client chooses to interact with certain resources based on what was learned from such hypermedia. But beyond that, there is no obligation for the server, no shared contract, no shared nothing.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;Especially can the client not rely on:&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;- the methods supported by the server for that resource&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;- the response the server will return for invoking that resource&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;- the implementation details or particular state changes that will occur on the server side.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;E.g. If you POST to an AtomPub collection, the server might well respond with a 202 instead of a 201, no matter what the AtomPub spec chose to say would/should/might happen.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;E.g. If you PUT to an AtomPub &#39;edit-URI&#39; the server might well inform you that PUT is not supported, advising you to use POST instead.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;You are (in my perception of your replies - which might be wrong of course) trying to fit an RPC mental model onto REST because you are insisting on *shared* understanding and that the server &#39;knows the application&#39; (which it does in RPC style architectures)&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;Jan&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
